 NAT Gateway (One-Way Internet)

 ðŸ”¹ What is a NAT Gateway

A NAT Gateway allows private servers (servers without public IPs) to access the internet, but prevents inbound connections from the internet.

 Think of it as a one-way door:

   Outbound traffic â†’ allowed
   Inbound traffic â†’ blocked

 Private servers remain secure because they are not directly exposed.



 ðŸ”¹ Why NAT Gateway is Needed

1ï¸âƒ£ Security best practice

 Private servers (e.g., databases) should not be accessible from the internet
 NAT lets them reach updates or external APIs safely

2ï¸âƒ£ Outbound internet access

 Servers need to download OS updates, packages, or dependencies

3ï¸âƒ£ Keep architecture clean

 Public servers handle external traffic
 Private servers handle internal work only



 ðŸ”¹ Linux Admin Role 

 OS patching

   Update Linux servers in private subnet

  yum update -y    RHEL/CentOS
  apt update && apt upgrade -y    Ubuntu


 Package installation

   Install software from internet repositories

 Connectivity troubleshooting

   If private server cannot reach internet â†’ check NAT Gateway configuration



 ðŸ”¹ Real-Life Example 

 Private subnet: `10.0.2.0/24` (database servers)
 NAT Gateway in public subnet: allows private servers to download updates
 Result:
   Database gets updates
   Database is not reachable from internet



